{"id":"1401.4287","submitter":"Vadim Atrazhev V.","authors":"Vadim V. Atrazhev, Tatiana Yu. Astakhova, Dmitry V. Dmitriev, Nikolay\n  S. Erikhman, Vadim I. Sultanov, Timothy Patterson and Sergei F. Burlatsky","title":"The model of stress distribution in polymer electrolyte membrane","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Journal of The Electrochemical Society, 160 (10) F1129-F1137\n  (2013)","doi":"10.1149/2.079310jes","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.chem-ph cond-mat.soft","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  An analytical model of mechanical stress in a polymer electrolyte membrane\n(PEM) of a hydrogen/air fuel cell with porous Water Transfer Plates (WTP) is\ndeveloped in this work. The model considers a mechanical stress in the membrane\nis a result of the cell load cycling under constant oxygen utilization. The\nload cycling causes the cycling of the inlet gas flow rate, which results in\nthe membrane hydration/dehydration close to the gas inlet.\nHydration/dehydration of the membrane leads to membrane swelling/shrinking,\nwhich causes mechanical stress in the constrained membrane. Mechanical stress\nresults in through-plane crack formation. Thereby, the mechanical stress in the\nmembrane causes mechanical failure of the membrane, limiting fuel cell\nlifetime. The model predicts the stress in the membrane as a function of the\ncell geometry, membrane material properties and operation conditions. The model\nwas applied for stress calculation in GORE-SELECT.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 17 Jan 2014 09:45:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-01-20"}
