yze the more general situation where lepton number\nviolating CP asymmetries are present and actively participate in the generation\nof the $B-L$ asymmetry, pointing out that as long as $L$-violating triplet\ndecays are still in thermal equilibrium when the triplet gauge scattering\nprocesses decouple, flavor effects can be striking, allowing to avoid all\nwashout suppression effects from seesaw interactions. In this case the amount\nof $B-L$ asymmetry produced is limited only by a universal gauge suppression\neffect, which nevertheless goes away for large triplet decay rates.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 17 Jan 2014 14:04:26 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 30 Jul 2014 12:37:30 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-18"}
